YES

Here's the interpretation using set theory:

Let A = {all chocolate cakes}, B = {all cakes}, and C = {sweet things}.

The statement can be represented as:

A ⊆ B
B ∩ C ≠ ∅

Therefore, A ∩ (B ∩ C) ≠ ∅.

Since A ⊆ B, we know that every element in A is also an element of B. Additionally, we know that there exists an element in B that is also an element of C (i.e., B ∩ C ≠ ∅). From this, we can conclude that there exists an element in A that is also an element of C (i.e., A ∩ (B ∩ C) ≠ ∅). So, some chocolate cakes are sweet.
